    "text": "2.1 Vulnerability-Inducing Commit The concept of Vulnerability-Inducing Commit (VIC) is conceptually derived from the well- established and widely studied notion of Bug-Inducing Commit (BIC) [ 39 ], which is formally defined as the commit in a version control system where a software defect is first introduced. Building on this foundational premise, a considerable number of researchers have dedicated ef- forts to proposing and refining improved techniques for identifying BICs, most notably through the development and refinement of various SZZ-based algorithms [ 14 , 24 , 32 ]. The original SZZ algorithm fundamentally operates by systematically tracing backward through the version control history starting from a known bug-fixing commit, with the objective of precisely identifying and isolating the specific earlier commits that were responsible for introducing the particular lines of code that were later modified or deleted in that fix, a process typically and effectively using built-in version control annotation or blame mechanisms. These subsequent variants of the SZZ methodology significantly enhance the original method by addressing common issues such as noise, inaccurate line mapping, and commit granularity. Furthermore, with the recent and rapid emergence of powerful large language models, a growing body of recent studies has actively explored their potential integration into and enhancement of traditional SZZ-based workflows. For example, Tang et al. introduced LLM4SZZ [ 43 ], which leverages the semantic capabilities of language models to more accurately detect bug-inducing commits based on patch content and commit messages. By understanding the contextual meaning of code changes and commit descriptions, LLM4SZZ reduces false positives and identify extra commits that all baselines cannot. Given the success of SZZ in the bug localization domain, it has subsequently been adapted for vulnerability analysis, particularly in identifying vulnerability-inducing commits and inferring vulnerability-affecting version ranges. One notable and direct adaptation of this methodology is exemplified by V-SZZ [ 9 ], which operates by attempting to systematically trace backwards from a known vulnerability-fixing commit in order to identify and pinpoint the specific earlier commit that originally introduced the security flaw, primarily through the analysis of lines of code that were deleted within the fix patch. However, this direct adaptation introduces significant limitations. Specifically, V-SZZ assumes all deleted lines are vulnerable and fails to address fix commits that only contain added lines. More importantly, despite the shared conceptual basis, there are fundamental differences between bugs and vulnerabilities that are often not well accounted for in these approaches. For instance, while bugs are frequently introduced in recent commits and can often be detected within a short temporal",
